Bill Ackman started his current hedge fund, Pershing Square LP (PSLP), in 2=
004. PSLP is kind of what you think of when you think of a hedge fund
  [1]
: It raised lots of money from big investors, it invests in concentrated be=
ts (largely on stocks but also credit, interest rates, other things), it ha=
s done activist long investing and also short selling,
  [2]
=C2=A0and it charges pretty close to the traditional =E2=80=9C2 and 20=E2=
=80=9D fee structure, or rather 1.5 and 20: Investors pay a 1.5% annual man=
agement fee on their assets, plus 20% of their gains.
  [3]

In 2014, Ackman launched a new fund, Pershing Square Holdings (PSH).
  [4]
=C2=A0PSH is=C2=A0not a traditional hedge fund: It is a publicly traded clo=
sed-end fund. Investors could put money into PSH =E2=80=94=C2=A0they could =
buy shares of the fund from PSH =E2=80=94=C2=A0but they can=E2=80=99t take =
money=C2=A0out; if they want their money back they have to sell shares on t=
he stock exchange. This makes PSH a =E2=80=9Cpermanent capital vehicle,=E2=
=80=9D which is useful for a hedge fund manager making big bets: If investo=
rs are dissatisfied, they can=E2=80=99t just demand their money back. I   s=
ometimes say that the essential skill of a hedge fund manager is not pickin=
g stocks that go up but rather=C2=A0continuing to run a hedge fund, and in =
some sense raising a multibillion-dollar permanent capital vehicle when tim=
es are good is a the very best possible thing for a hedge fund manager to d=
o. And in 2014=C2=A0Ackman did it.
As of 2024, Ackman manages about $18 billion, of which about $14.6 billion =
is in PSH, about $2 billion is in the hedge fund and about $1.6 billion is =
in a special Universal Music Group investment vehicle.
  [5]
=C2=A0So most of the money these days is in PSH. (Ackman also has a SPARC, =
which I love and have discussed before, but it=E2=80=99s not really relevan=
t here so I=E2=80=99m not going to mention it again.) Roughly $4.5 billion =
of that money is =E2=80=9Cinsider capital=E2=80=9D from Ackman himself and =
his employees. In some loose sense, Ackman is less a =E2=80=9Chedge fund ma=
nager=E2=80=9D and more a =E2=80=9Cmanager of a publicly traded investment =
vehicle.=E2=80=9D
Well.=C2=A0PSH is not a traditional hedge fund, in being closed-end and pub=
licly traded, but in other ways it does look a lot like a hedge fund. It ch=
arges, not 2 and 20, but 1.5 and 16: a 1.5% management fee on assets=C2=A0a=
nd a 16% performance fee on gains. Like PSLP, PSH has made mostly concentra=
ted bets on stocks, long and short, but it has also had some nice derivativ=
es trades. It operates with some leverage (unlike PSLP), roughly 18% of cap=
ital. It is hedge fund-y.
Another thing that is hedge fund-y about it is that, if you are a regular i=
nvestor in the US, you can=E2=80=99t buy it. PSH is incorporated in Guernse=
y and listed on stock exchanges in Amsterdam and London. This is a little o=
dd: Ackman lives and works in New York, he has a high public profile in the=
 US, and Pershing Square=E2=80=99s investments are largely US stocks. Why r=
aise his public money in Europe?
The basic answer seems to be that the US regulates public investment funds =
more strictly than Europe does. For one thing, the US Securities and Exchan=
ge Commission rules for =E2=80=9Cregistered investment companies=E2=80=9D r=
egulate the use of=C2=A0leverage,  derivatives=C2=A0and=C2=A0short selling;=
 if you are a swashbuckling hedge fund manager who wants the freedom to inv=
est anywhere, you might find those rules too constraining. Also, though =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0maybe more importantly =E2=80=94=C2=A0US registered investment =
companies generally  can=E2=80=99t charge performance fees. If you are a he=
dge fund manager who wants the freedom to charge 2 and 20, or 1.5 and 16, y=
ou can=E2=80=99t do it in a public vehicle in the US.
In 2004, Bill Ackman was a swashbuckling hedge fund manager who wanted the =
freedom to invest anywhere and charge 1.5 and 20, so he started a hedge fun=
d. In 2014, Bill Ackman was a swashbuckling hedge=C2=A0fund manager who wan=
ted the freedom to invest anywhere and charge 1.5 and 16, and also raise pu=
blic permanent capital, so he started a European public fund.
In 2024, Bloomberg=E2=80=99s   Annie Massa reports:

Billionaire Bill Ackman is courting small-scale US investors.
His investment firm Pershing Square Capital Management plans to start a new=
 fund called Pershing Square USA for retail investors, which would trade on=
 the New York Stock Exchange, according to a regulatory filing Wednesday. T=
he fund, with the ticker PSUS, will invest in one- to two-dozen large, unde=
rvalued companies in North America.=C2=A0
Pershing Square=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cbrand-name profile and broad retail foll=
owing will drive substantial investor interest,=E2=80=9D according to the f=
iling. ...
Ackman=E2=80=99s showboating has been on display in recent months as he spo=
uted fiery takes on a range of topics to his 1.2 million followers on X, fo=
rmerly Twitter. ...
On Wednesday, he took to X to announce the new retail fund.

Here=E2=80=99s  the prospectus, and here=E2=80=99s  the tweet. Like PSH, PS=
US will be a closed-end fund. What is the difference between PSUS=C2=A0and =
PSH? Well:
=09We don=E2=80=99t know what PSUS=C2=A0will invest in,  but it =E2=80=9Cex=
pects that the substantial majority of the Fund=E2=80=99s investment portfo=
lio will be invested in 12 to 24 core holdings in large-capitalization, inv=
estment grade, free-cash-flow-generative North American durable growth comp=
anies.=E2=80=9D It will also =E2=80=9Copportunistically utilize hedges to p=
rotect the portfolio against specific macroeconomic risks and capitalize on=
 market volatility.=E2=80=9D PSH=E2=80=99s most recent  investor presentati=
on=C2=A0lists 10 stocks =E2=80=94 large North American public companies =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0plus an energy hedge and interest rate swaptions. So it seems r=
easonable to assume that PSUS=C2=A0and PSH will be more or less mirrors of =
each other in terms of their investments.=C2=A0=09PSUS=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cdoes n=
ot intend to borrow money during its initial year of operations,=E2=80=9D b=
ut =E2=80=9Creserves the right to borrow money,=E2=80=9D subject to US inve=
stment company rules. PSH has a bit of leverage, but not that much, about 1=
8% of assets. It seems reasonable to assume that PSUS=C2=A0and PSH won=E2=
=80=99t be that far off each other in terms of leverage.=09Surely the big d=
ifference is fees? PSH charges a 1.5% management fee and a 16% performance =
fee. PSUS, as a US registered investment company, will charge only a 2% man=
agement fee, and will waive even that for the first year, for a total fee o=
f $0. =E2=80=9CThe Fund will not be subject to any performance fees. The Fu=
nd believes that this has the potential to meaningfully improve long-term N=
AV per Common Share performance,=E2=80=9D says the prospectus.

But that difference will close too: Ackman intends to credit 20% of his PSU=
S=C2=A0management fees against the PSH performance fees.
  [6]
=C2=A0In a  presentation to PSH investors yesterday, Pershing Square descri=
bes the =E2=80=9Cillustrative fee reduction impact=E2=80=9D from PSUS: If P=
SUS=C2=A0raises $10 billion (!), it will get paid $200 million a year in ma=
nagement fees (after the first year), which will reduce PSH=E2=80=99s perfo=
rmance fees by $40 million. =E2=80=9CAssuming PSH generates 15% gross retur=
ns, the fee offset from the new fund alone will reduce PSH=E2=80=99s perfor=
mance fee percentage from 16.0% to 13.5%.=E2=80=9D (If it makes 5%, the fee=
 will go be only 6.5%.)
The point in that paragraph is less the math and more that Ackman apparentl=
y expects to raise $10 billion in the new fund.
I guess the question here is: Why now? Why did Ackman launch a European pub=
lic fund 10 years ago, and decide now to launch a US one?
Here are two ways of thinking about it. One is that PSH has generally trade=
d at a discount to its net asset value: It has about $14.6 billion of asset=
s under management, $12.2 billion of net asset value (after subtracting lev=
erage), but a market value of only about $9 billion, a 26% discount. The ma=
rket does not give Ackman full credit for his portfolio. And that discount =
has largely grown over time; it was=C2=A0smaller when PSH launched than it =
is now.
One thing that this means is that Ackman can=E2=80=99t raise=C2=A0more=C2=
=A0money efficiently in PSH: Selling new shares at a discount to net asset =
value would dilute existing shareholders (including himself). Another thing=
 it means is that=C2=A0stock buybacks=C2=A0are efficient: PSH can buy its o=
wn shares back for less than they=E2=80=99re worth, which is accretive.
I don=E2=80=99t know exactly why PSH trades at a discount, but it does seem=
 plausible to think something like =E2=80=9Ca Bill Ackman vehicle would tra=
de at a higher value in New York, a very liquid stock market where everyone=
 knows Bill Ackman, than in Amsterdam.=E2=80=9D And in fact yesterday=E2=80=
=99s  investor=C2=A0presentation discusses the =E2=80=9Cstrategies to addre=
ss the discount=E2=80=9D that PSH has used, including buybacks, dividends a=
nd =E2=80=9Cglobal marketing efforts outside of the United States.=E2=80=9D=
 And =E2=80=9Cin 2023, we thoroughly examined the options for a U.S. listin=
g to increase the number of investors who can own PSH,=E2=80=9D because=C2=
=A0obviously=C2=A0marketing efforts=C2=A0inside=C2=A0the US will go over be=
tter.=C2=A0But it didn=E2=80=99t work; it was too complicated to turn PSH i=
nto a US company. So Ackman is starting a=C2=A0new=C2=A0US company to, I su=
spect, more or less clone PSH.
Presumably the expectation is that, by increasing the number of investors w=
ho can own=C2=A0some flavor of Pershing Square, Ackman will be able to rais=
e money at less of a discount. (Maybe a premium?) Over time you raise most =
of your money in the US, in PSUS, where investors will pay more for the por=
tfolio, and you do buybacks to retire shares in Europe, in PSH, where they =
won=E2=80=99t.
  [7]
=C2=A0In 2014 Ackman raised his permanent capital in Europe, which worked b=
ut was kind of an odd fit for his profile; in 2024 he will shift it more to=
ward the US, which is a better fit. He can buy back PSH low and, probably, =
sell PSUS=C2=A0high.
The other way to think about it is, look, you=E2=80=99ve got management fee=
s and you=E2=80=99ve got performance fees. When you are a young hotshot hed=
ge fund manager just starting out, you want those performance fees. You don=
=E2=80=99t have that much money of your own (you are young), you plan to ma=
ke a lot of money for your investors (you are confident), and you want to t=
ake a lot of that performance for yourself. Management fees are nice, but n=
ot that important, because you can=E2=80=99t raise=C2=A0that=C2=A0much mone=
y when you=E2=80=99re just starting out.
But when you are a mature famous hedge fund manager, the performance fees a=
re less important. You have billions of dollars of your own money in the fu=
nd now, so if your performance is good you will make lots of money just on =
the appreciation of your own money. But the management fees are more attrac=
tive: You are now famous, so you can put out a tweet and expect to raise=C2=
=A0$10 billion=C2=A0of new money, which will pay you a $200 million fee for=
ever.
  [8]
=C2=A0That starts to look nice.
Not that nice, now. PSH  returned 26.7% to investors last year, net of fees=
. The rough math is that, on $12 billion of net assets, Pershing Square pro=
bably charged PSH investors about $180 million of management fees and more =
than $400 million of performance fees.=C2=A0Under the PSUS=C2=A0fee structu=
re, investors would have done better =E2=80=94=C2=A0Pershing Square says th=
eir net return would have been 30.6% =E2=80=94=C2=A0and Ackman would have d=
one worse; he would have charged less than half as much in fees.=C2=A0
But in the long run, I mean, maybe you can=E2=80=99t be a hotshot hedge fun=
d manager forever. But you can manage a permanent capital vehicle forever; =
that=E2=80=99s the point. Raising enthusiastic permanent capital when enthu=
siasm is high =E2=80=94=C2=A0and trading some fees for permanence =E2=80=94=
 might be a good idea.

