      Block trades
   =20
 =20

We   talked last month about some bad stuff that Morgan Stanley did in its =
block trading business. A big holder of stock =E2=80=94=C2=A0say, a private=
 equity firm with a big stake in a company it had already taken public =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0would decide to sell the stock all at once. It would call Morga=
n Stanley at like noon and say =E2=80=9Cwe want to sell all our stock in Co=
mpany X, we=E2=80=99re going to ask you for a bid at 4:05 p.m. today, get r=
eady, but=C2=A0don=E2=80=99t tell anyone.=E2=80=9D And the holder would cal=
l a few other banks with the same message. And then Morgan Stanley was supp=
osed to sit down and decide what price to bid on the stock, and if it was t=
he highest bidder at 4:05 p.m. it would win the block trade, buy the stock =
at its bid price, and then turn around and sell the stock to hedge funds an=
d other investors, as quickly as possible and preferably before the market =
opened the next day. But if it won the bid, it would be at risk: If it coul=
dn=E2=80=99t sell the stock for more than it paid for it, it would lose mon=
ey.
One thing that would make this process easier and less risky for Morgan Sta=
nley would be if, between noon and 4 p.m., it were to call a bunch of hedge=
 funds and say =E2=80=9Chey, we got a block of Company X coming this evenin=
g, would you buy some, and if so for what price?=E2=80=9D If it pre-sold th=
e block before putting in a bid, it could be confident that it would be abl=
e to resell the stock to investors and make money. But the seller=C2=A0did =
not want Morgan Stanley to do that, because if word leaked out about the bl=
ock, people would know that a lot of supply was coming and that the stock w=
ould go down, so they would sell the stock first, which would lower the pri=
ce that the seller could get. So the seller would tell Morgan Stanley, in w=
riting, emphatically, =E2=80=9Cdon=E2=80=99t tell anyone about this block, =
don=E2=80=99t even drop any hints about it, don=E2=80=99t have even generic=
 conversations about the sector with investors, keep this really secret.=E2=
=80=9D
And Morgan Stanley would agree to those terms, and then it would go out and=
 tell a bunch of hedge funds about the block anyway, and some of the hedge =
funds would short the stock and make a quick easy profit when the block tra=
de came, and the stock=C2=A0would go down and the seller=C2=A0would get a w=
orse price=C2=A0and eventually Morgan Stanley got in trouble and paid sever=
al hundred million dollars in fines.
One lingering question might be: Should the=C2=A0hedge funds=C2=A0get in tr=
ouble? It sort of seems like Morgan Stanley had inside information, and it =
tipped that information to the hedge funds, and they traded on it. Is that =
bad?
It=E2=80=99s tricky. The   traditional insider trading analysis would say t=
hat it is illegal to trade on information that someone has misappropriated,=
 if you know (or ought to know) that it was misappropriated. If your brothe=
r-in-law is an investment banker, and he tells you =E2=80=9Chey I=E2=80=99m=
 working on a deal, you should buy call options=C2=A0on the target,=E2=80=
=9D you really ought to know that he=E2=80=99s not supposed to do that.
  [9]
=C2=A0And=C2=A0many=C2=A0insider tips will look like that; you will have so=
me reason to suspect that person telling you the information really shouldn=
=E2=80=99t be.
With the block trade leaks, the  charges against Morgan Stanley suggest tha=
t some of its customers might have had some idea that something a bit shady=
 was going on:
Hedge fund investors who received confidential information from the Head of=
 the Desk and Employee-1 about upcoming blocks recognized that this informa=
tion allowed them to profit in ways they otherwise would not have. For exam=
ple, an investor working at a Nevada- based hedge fund (=E2=80=9CInvestor-3=
=E2=80=9D) told the Head of the Desk in an August 2021 call, =E2=80=9CI kno=
w who my daddy is,=E2=80=9D referring to the assistance that the Head of th=
e Desk had provided Investor-3 in profiting from block trades.
You don=E2=80=99t say =E2=80=9CI know who my daddy is=E2=80=9D to your sale=
sperson unless you know you are getting some sort of weird personal favor.=
=C2=A0
But I=E2=80=99m not sure that=E2=80=99s true for all of them? In general, i=
f someone from a sales or syndicate desk at a big bank calls you and says =
=E2=80=9Chey we have a bunch of Stock X coming, you want some,=E2=80=9D you=
 don=E2=80=99t necessarily have any reason to think that the salesperson is=
 doing anything nefarious. His job is to sell you stock! If he calls you up=
 asking if you want to buy stock, you might assume that he=E2=80=99s just d=
oing his job. You might assume that he is shopping around the shares with t=
he seller=E2=80=99s permission, that he is trying to drum up interest by ma=
king the sale public.=C2=A0
I mean, you might not, because actually with a block trade that would be ki=
nd of weird. (The salesperson might=C2=A0call you in advance with the compa=
ny=E2=80=99s permission, but ordinarily he=E2=80=99d =E2=80=9Cwall-cross=E2=
=80=9D you first, making you agree not to trade until the sale is public.) =
And if you got a call from a salesperson saying =E2=80=9CI have some Stock =
X to sell, you want some,=E2=80=9D and you=C2=A0hung up and immediately=C2=
=A0shorted the stock yourself, that=E2=80=99s kind of rude.
  [10]
=C2=A0Still.=C2=A0Bloomberg=E2=80=99s   Sridhar Natarajan and Katherine Bur=
ton report:

When the US punished Morgan Stanley for leaking upcoming stock trades to fa=
vored clients, it kept the list of recipients secret. They include one of W=
all Street=E2=80=99s biggest players: Citadel.
A trader at Ken Griffin=E2=80=99s giant hedge fund was among a coterie of e=
xecutives described anonymously in Morgan Stanley=E2=80=99s settlements wit=
h the government, according to people with knowledge of the matter. ...
Prosecutors haven=E2=80=99t accused any buy-side participants that allegedl=
y received tips of any wrongdoing. =E2=80=A6
Not every leak resulted in hedge fund managers trading before blocks of sto=
ck were sold. In some cases the sellers aborted their plans, which is what =
happened on two trades that were leaked to Citadel. Industry lawyers also a=
rgued that if firms did trade, they didn=E2=80=99t break any laws, because =
they hadn=E2=80=99t signed confidentiality pacts with the bank.
Hedge funds on the receiving end of information from a Morgan Stanley execu=
tive were =E2=80=9Centitled to assume he was following his firm=E2=80=99s r=
ules,=E2=80=9D said Cristie Ford, a former Davis Polk lawyer who now teache=
s at the University of British Columbia. The nature of interactions is such=
 that =E2=80=9Csome of it is based on rumors, some of it is based on hunche=
s, and some of it is based on hypothetical questions from equity desks.=E2=
=80=9D

I do think that's basically right. If you meet your buddy from Morgan Stanl=
ey on the golf course and he says =E2=80=9Chey I=E2=80=99ve got a hot tip f=
or you, don=E2=80=99t tell anyone,=E2=80=9D you can assume he=E2=80=99s up =
to no good. If he calls you at your desk, from his desk, on a recorded line=
, saying =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99ve got a deal coming and we=E2=80=99d like you=
 to be in it,=E2=80=9D I think you=E2=80=99re allowed to assume it=E2=80=99=
s fine. Even though, here, it was not.

