      Should index funds be illegal?
   =20
 =20

One finance hypothetical that people like to ponder is: If 90% of the stock=
 market was held by index funds, would that be good or bad for efficiency? =
Would the prices of stocks better incorporate all information about those s=
tocks, or worse? There are arguments both ways:
=09The negative view is that, if almost everyone indexes, there=E2=80=99s n=
o one around to do the fundamental research to make sure that prices are ac=
curate. Hedge funds and other active managers won=E2=80=99t have enough mon=
ey to manage, they won=E2=80=99t be able to invest in research and technolo=
gy, and so there won=E2=80=99t be anyone selling overvalued stocks and buyi=
ng undervalued ones. It=E2=80=99ll just be index funds blindly buying at wh=
atever the market price is, and that price will be disconnected from fundam=
entals, and the stock market will no longer be good at allocating capital t=
o its best uses. =E2=80=9CPassive Investing is Worse Than Marxism,=E2=80=9D=
 in the words of a somewhat famous Sanford C. Bernstein & Co. equity resear=
ch note.=09The positive view is that, the more money that is indexed, the m=
ore=C2=A0influence=C2=A0each active manager will have on the stock. If most=
 people index, then active management will shrink, but the best active mana=
gers will keep their jobs, and their trading with each other is what will m=
ove stocks. Index funds will free-ride on their efforts, but they will stil=
l have enough money to make those efforts worthwhile, and those efforts =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0not the free-riding =E2=80=94=C2=A0will determine the price.
  [11]



It is kind of an empirical question, though. Here is =E2=80=9CIndexing and =
the Incorporation of Exogenous Information Shocks to Stock Prices,=E2=80=9D=
 by=C2=A0Randall Morck and M. Deniz Yavuz, with some negative conclusions:
Savings increasingly flow to low-cost index funds, which simply buy and hol=
d the stocks in a major index, such as the S&P 500. Increased indexing impe=
des incorporation of idiosyncratic information into stock prices. We limit =
endogeneity bias by showing that exogenous idiosyncratic currency shocks in=
duce smaller idiosyncratic moves in the stock prices of currency-sensitive =
firms in proximate time windows when in the index than when not in it. Incr=
eased indexing thus appears to be undermining the efficient markets hypothe=
sis that supports its viability.
The basic idea is that there are some public companies whose fundamental pe=
rformance is particularly sensitive to exchange rates: They do a lot of bus=
iness in Europe (or wherever), and so their profits fluctuate when the euro=
/dollar exchange rate goes up or down. An efficient market would, arguably,=
 reflect this: When the euro goes up, those companies=E2=80=99 stocks would=
 go up, or whatever. And they find that the market is more efficient for co=
mpanies outside the S&P 500:
Our main tests reveal an economically and statistically significant 60% low=
er (-0.34 point estimate difference) in stocks=E2=80=99 idiosyncratic curre=
ncy sensitivity when in versus not in the S&P 500, whereas the magnitude of=
 idiosyncratic currency shocks does not change significantly. The result is=
 highly robust: It is evident in stocks added to the index, stocks dropped =
from the index, and both combined. It is robust across reasonable alternati=
ve ways of estimating idiosyncratic returns. Moreover, this difference in p=
oint estimate becomes more negative over time in lockstep with plausible pr=
oxies for the rising importance of indexing. These results are consistent w=
ith=C2=A0indexing impairing the incorporation of firm-specific information =
into stock prices.
