      Ozempic is bad for business?
   =20
 =20

We have  talked a few times before about how appetite-suppressing drugs lik=
e Ozempic are bad for the sales of snack-food companies, and how universal =
investors who own both the drug companies that sell those drugs, and the fo=
od companies that lose out to them, might have mixed feelings. As an amusin=
g theoretical matter, you could imagine those universal shareholders callin=
g up the drug-company CEOs and saying =E2=80=9Cstop selling these drugs, yo=
ur profits from the drugs are not enough to offset our losses from snack fo=
ods.=E2=80=9D
As a practical matter that seems unlikely. For one thing, it=E2=80=99s prob=
ably not true: Maybe Ozempic will suppress snack-food profits but increase,=
 say,  airline profits, enough that the universal holders are better off ov=
erall. For another thing, it=E2=80=99s not like universal shareholders real=
ly make these calls, probably: It is theoretically interesting to imagine u=
niversal shareholders like BlackRock and Vanguard and Fidelity instructing =
corporate chief executive officers to maximize portfolio profits rather tha=
n their own companies=E2=80=99=C2=A0profits, but they probably don=E2=80=99=
t really do that. Also it just so happens that the drug companies that make=
 these drugs  have unusual shareholder situations that somewhat insulate th=
em from the usual universal owners of the stock market.=C2=A0
Still the CEOs  do talk to each other:

Makers of everything from snack food to knee implants are facing a potentia=
l threat from Novo Nordisk A/S=E2=80=99s powerful appetite-suppressing trea=
tments. So they=E2=80=99re calling the drugmaker for advice.
=E2=80=9CA couple of CEOs from, say, food companies have been calling me,=
=E2=80=9D Novo Chief Executive Officer Lars Fruergaard Jorgensen said durin=
g a wide-ranging discussion in New York. He declined to name names, saying =
questions had centered on how the drugs work and how fast they would roll o=
ut. =E2=80=9CThey are scared about it.=E2=80=9D

I love the idea of Jorgensen getting calls from snack-food companies to ple=
ad with him, saying =E2=80=9Cyou are putting me out of business, please jus=
t let me keep selling my potato chips.=E2=80=9D

