</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bill Ackman started his current hedge fund, Pe=
rshing Square LP (PSLP), in 2004. PSLP is kind of what you think of when yo=
u think of a hedge fund<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" sty=
le=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width=
: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; =
background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>: It raised lots of money from big investors, it invests in concentrate=
d bets (largely on stocks but also credit, interest rates, other things), i=
t has done activist long investing and also short selling,<a class=3D"footn=
ote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: n=
one !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bor=
der-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important=
; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0and it charges pretty close to the traditional =E2=80=9C2 and 20=
=E2=80=9D fee structure, or rather 1.5 and 20: Investors pay a 1.5% annual =
management fee on their assets, plus 20% of their gains.<a class=3D"footnot=
e-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; =
display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In 2014, Ackman launched a new fund, Pershing =
Square Holdings (PSH).<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" styl=
e=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width:=
 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; b=
ackground-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>=C2=A0PSH is=C2=A0<em>not </em>a traditional hedge fund: It is a public=
ly traded closed-end fund. Investors could put money into PSH =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0they could buy shares of the fund from PSH =E2=80=94=C2=A0but they can=
=E2=80=99t take money=C2=A0<em>out</em>; if they want their money back they=
 have to sell shares on the stock exchange. This makes PSH a =E2=80=9Cperma=
nent capital vehicle,=E2=80=9D which is useful for a hedge fund manager mak=
ing big bets: If investors are dissatisfied, they can=E2=80=99t just demand=
 their money back. I <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cli=
ck/34283789.285388/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVz=
LzIwMTgtMDctMDUvaXQtcy1iZXR0ZXItdG8tYmUtcmljaC10aGFuLXJpZ2h0P2NtcGlkPUJCRDA=
yMDgyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJn=
V0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDIwOCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a2=
3cB7dc7002c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blan=
k" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;">  sometimes say</a> that the essential skill of a hedg=
e fund manager is not picking stocks that go up but rather=C2=A0<em>continu=
ing to run a hedge fund</em>, and in some sense raising a multibillion-doll=
ar permanent capital vehicle when times are good is a the very best possibl=
e thing for a hedge fund manager to do. And in 2014=C2=A0Ackman did it.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As of 2024, Ackman manages about $18 billion, =
of which about $14.6 billion is in PSH, about $2 billion is in the hedge fu=
nd and about $1.6 billion is in a special Universal Music Group investment =
vehicle.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-colo=
r: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a>=C2=A0So most of the money these days is in PSH. (Ackman also <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34283789.285388/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMTEtMjkvYmlsbC1hY2tt=
YW4taGFzLWEtc3BhcmM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDIwODI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWF=
pbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwMjA4JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb2=
5leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB81e13e53" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsc=
ope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">has a SPARC</a>, whic=
h I love and have discussed before, but it=E2=80=99s not really relevant he=
re so I=E2=80=99m not going to mention it again.) Roughly $4.5 billion of t=
hat money is =E2=80=9Cinsider capital=E2=80=9D from Ackman himself and his =
employees. In some loose sense, Ackman is less a =E2=80=9Chedge fund manage=
r=E2=80=9D and more a =E2=80=9Cmanager of a publicly traded investment vehi=
cle.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Well.=C2=A0PSH is not a traditional hedge fund=
, in being closed-end and publicly traded, but in other ways it does look a=
 lot like a hedge fund. It charges, not 2 and 20, but 1.5 and 16: a 1.5% ma=
nagement fee on assets=C2=A0and a 16% performance fee on gains. Like PSLP, =
PSH has made mostly concentrated bets on stocks, long and short, but it has=
 also had <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34283789=
.285388/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMucGVyc2hpbmdzcXVhcmVob2xkaW5ncy5jb20vMjAyMi8xMC8=
wNzE1MDkxNy9MZXR0ZXItdG8tU2hhcmVob2xkZXJzLUV4Y2VycHRlZC1mcm9tLXRoZS0yMDIwLV=
NlbWlhbm51YWwtRmluYW5jaWFsLVN0YXRlbWVudC5wZGY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB891b=
d031" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" styl=
e=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width:=
 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-=
color: #ccc;">some nice derivatives</a> trades. It operates with some lever=
age (unlike PSLP), roughly <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.c=
om/click/34283789.285388/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMucGVyc2hpbmdzcXVhcmVob2xkaW5ncy=
5jb20vMjAyMy8wOC8xODExMjA0MC9QZXJzaGluZy1TcXVhcmUtSG9sZGluZ3MtTHRkLi1KdW5lL=
TIwMjMtSW50ZXJpbS5wZGY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB95d71dfe" itemprop=3D"Story=
Link" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; te=
xt-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-col=
or: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">18% of ca=
pital</a>. It is hedge fund-y.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Another thing that is hedge fund-y about it is=
 that, if you are a regular investor in the US, you can=E2=80=99t buy it. P=
SH is incorporated in Guernsey and listed on stock exchanges in Amsterdam a=
nd London. This is a little odd: Ackman lives and works in New York, he has=
 a high public profile in the US, and Pershing Square=E2=80=99s investments=
 are largely US stocks. Why raise his public money in Europe?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The basic answer seems to be that the US regul=
ates public investment funds more strictly than Europe does. For one thing,=
 the US Securities and Exchange Commission rules for =E2=80=9Cregistered in=
vestment companies=E2=80=9D regulate the use of=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://lin=
k.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34283789.285388/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuaWNpLm9y=
Zy9mYXFzL2ZhcS9vdGhlci9mYXFzX2Nsb3NlZF9lbmQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3de8a2=
a9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">leverage</a>, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.c=
om/click/34283789.285388/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9pbnZlc3RtZW50L2Rlcml2YX=
RpdmVzLXVzZS1yZWdpc3RlcmVkLWludmVzdG1lbnQtYnVzaW5lc3MtZGV2ZWxvcG1lbnQtY29tc=
GFuaWVz/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6eedee4f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> derivatives</a>=C2=A0an=
d=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34283789.28=
5388/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9kaXZpc2lvbnMvaW52ZXN0bWVudC9zZW5pb3JzZWN1cm=
l0aWVzLWJpYmxpb2dyYXBoeQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc6918bed" itemprop=3D"Sto=
ryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; =
text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-c=
olor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">short s=
elling</a>; if you are a swashbuckling hedge fund manager who wants the fre=
edom to invest anywhere, you might find those rules too constraining. Also,=
 though =E2=80=94=C2=A0maybe more importantly =E2=80=94=C2=A0US registered =
investment companies generally <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusine=
ss.com/click/34283789.285388/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubGF3LmNvcm5lbGwuZWR1L3VzY29kZS=
90ZXh0LzE1LzgwYi01/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2a207092" itemprop=3D"StoryLink=
" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> can=E2=80=99=
t charge performance fees</a>. If you are a hedge fund manager who wants th=
e freedom to charge 2 and 20, or 1.5 and 16, you can=E2=80=99t do it in a p=
ublic vehicle in the US.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In 2004, Bill Ackman was a swashbuckling hedge=
 fund manager who wanted the freedom to invest anywhere and charge 1.5 and =
20, so he started a hedge fund. In 2014, Bill Ackman was a swashbuckling he=
dge=C2=A0fund manager who wanted the freedom to invest anywhere and charge =
1.5 and 16, and also raise public permanent capital, so he started a Europe=
an public fund.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In 2024, Bloomberg=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https:=
//link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34283789.285388/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmx=
vb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDItMDcvYWNrbWFuLXMtcGVyc2hpbmctc3=
F1YXJlLXRhcmdldHMtdXMtcmV0YWlsLWludmVzdG9ycy1pbi1uZXctZnVuZD9jbXBpZD1CQkQwM=
jA4MjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1=
dG1fdGVybT0yNDAyMDgmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23=
cB07d7db29" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backg=
round-color: #ccc;">  Annie Massa reports</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Billionaire Bill Ackman is courting small-scal=
e US investors.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">His investment firm Pershing Square Capital Ma=
nagement plans to start a new fund called Pershing Square USA for retail in=
vestors, which would trade on the New York Stock Exchange, according to a r=
egulatory filing Wednesday. The fund, with the ticker PSUS, will invest in =
one- to two-dozen large, undervalued companies in North America.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Pershing Square=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cbrand-name =
profile and broad retail following will drive substantial investor interest=
,=E2=80=9D according to the filing. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ackman=E2=80=99s showboating has been on displ=
ay in recent months as he spouted fiery takes on a range of topics to his 1=
.2 million followers on X, formerly Twitter. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On Wednesday, he took to X to announce the new=
 retail fund.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/34283789.285388/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoa=
XZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzIwMDI2NjAvMDAwMTE5MzEyNTI0MDI2MzAxL2Q2MjM3ODFkbjIuaHRt=
/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2b5346cb" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"ite=
mscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> the prospectus</a>, and here=
=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3428378=
9.285388/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9CaWxsQWNrbWFuL3N0YXR1cy8xNzU1MzE3MjM4NT=
c0MjUyMTUz/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3255ac49" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsc=
ope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> the tweet</a>. Like =
PSH, PSUS will be a closed-end fund. What is the difference between PSUS=C2=
=A0and PSH? Well:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">We don=E2=80=99t know what PSUS=C2=A0=
will invest in, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34=
283789.285388/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzIwMDI2N=
jAvMDAwMTE5MzEyNTI0MDI2MzAxL2Q2MjM3ODFkbjIuaHRt/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC2b=
5346cb" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" st=
yle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-widt=
h: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgroun=
d-color: #ccc;"> but it</a> =E2=80=9Cexpects that the substantial majority =
of the Fund=E2=80=99s investment portfolio will be invested in 12 to 24 cor=
e holdings in large-capitalization, investment grade, free-cash-flow-genera=
tive North American durable growth companies.=E2=80=9D It will also =E2=80=
=9Copportunistically utilize hedges to protect the portfolio against specif=
ic macroeconomic risks and capitalize on market volatility.=E2=80=9D PSH=E2=
=80=99s most recent <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/clic=
k/34283789.285388/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMucGVyc2hpbmdzcXVhcmVob2xkaW5ncy5jb20vM=
jAyNC8wMi8wNzExMTQwNS8yMDI0LUFubnVhbC1JbnZlc3Rvci1QcmVzZW50YXRpb24ucGRm/607=
f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa65bf515" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsco=
pe" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> investor presentation</a>=C2=A0lis=
ts 10 stocks =E2=80=94 large North American public companies =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0plus an energy hedge and interest rate swaptions. So it seems reasonable=
 to assume that PSUS=C2=A0and PSH will be more or less mirrors of each othe=
r in terms of their investments.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5=
px;">PSUS=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cdoes not intend to borrow money during its initial =
year of operations,=E2=80=9D but =E2=80=9Creserves the right to borrow mone=
y,=E2=80=9D subject to US investment company rules. PSH has a bit of levera=
ge, but not that much, about 18% of assets. It seems reasonable to assume t=
hat PSUS=C2=A0and PSH won=E2=80=99t be that far off each other in terms of =
leverage.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Surely the big differenc=
e is fees? PSH charges a 1.5% management fee and a 16% performance fee. PSU=
S, as a US registered investment company, will charge only a 2% management =
fee, and will waive even that for the first year, for a total fee of $0. =
=E2=80=9CThe Fund will not be subject to any performance fees. The Fund bel=
ieves that this has the potential to meaningfully improve long-term NAV per=
 Common Share performance,=E2=80=9D says the prospectus.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But that difference will close too: Ackman int=
ends to credit 20% of his PSUS=C2=A0management fees against the PSH perform=
ance fees.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-6" style=3D"color: =
#000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border=
-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-co=
lor: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a>=C2=A0In a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/342=
83789.285388/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMucGVyc2hpbmdzcXVhcmVob2xkaW5ncy5jb20vMjAyNC=
8wMi8wNzExMTQwNS8yMDI0LUFubnVhbC1JbnZlc3Rvci1QcmVzZW50YXRpb24ucGRm/607f07ce=
ef4b8524a319a23cCa65bf515" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" t=
arget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> presentation to PSH investors yesterday=
</a>, Pershing Square describes the =E2=80=9Cillustrative fee reduction imp=
act=E2=80=9D from PSUS: If PSUS=C2=A0raises $10 billion (!), it will get pa=
id $200 million a year in management fees (after the first year), which wil=
l reduce PSH=E2=80=99s performance fees by $40 million. =E2=80=9CAssuming P=
SH generates 15% gross returns, the fee offset from the new fund alone will=
 reduce PSH=E2=80=99s performance fee percentage from 16.0% to 13.5%.=E2=80=
=9D (If it makes 5%, the fee will go be only 6.5%.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The point in that paragraph is less the math a=
nd more that Ackman apparently expects to raise $10 billion in the new fund=
.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I guess the question here is: Why now? Why did=
 Ackman launch a European public fund 10 years ago, and decide now to launc=
h a US one?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here are two ways of thinking about it. One is=
 that PSH has generally traded at a discount to its net asset value: It has=
 about $14.6 billion of assets under management, $12.2 billion of net asset=
 value (after subtracting leverage), but a market value of only about $9 bi=
llion, a 26% discount. The market does not give Ackman full credit for his =
portfolio. And that discount has largely grown over time; it was=C2=A0small=
er when PSH launched than it is now.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One thing that this means is that Ackman can=
=E2=80=99t raise=C2=A0<em>more=C2=A0</em>money efficiently in PSH: Selling =
new shares at a discount to net asset value would dilute existing sharehold=
ers (including himself). Another thing it means is that=C2=A0<em>stock buyb=
acks=C2=A0</em>are efficient: PSH can buy its own shares back for less than=
 they=E2=80=99re worth, which is accretive.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t know exactly why PSH trades at=
 a discount, but it does seem plausible to think something like =E2=80=9Ca =
Bill Ackman vehicle would trade at a higher value in New York, a very liqui=
d stock market where everyone knows Bill Ackman, than in Amsterdam.=E2=80=
=9D And in fact yesterday=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergb=
usiness.com/click/34283789.285388/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMucGVyc2hpbmdzcXVhcmVob=
2xkaW5ncy5jb20vMjAyNC8wMi8wNzExMTQwNS8yMDI0LUFubnVhbC1JbnZlc3Rvci1QcmVzZW50=
YXRpb24ucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cDa65bf515" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" item=
scope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorat=
ion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00000=
0; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> investor=C2=A0pres=
entation</a> discusses the =E2=80=9Cstrategies to address the discount=E2=
=80=9D that PSH has used, including buybacks, dividends and =E2=80=9Cglobal=
 marketing efforts outside of the United States.=E2=80=9D And =E2=80=9Cin 2=
023, we thoroughly examined the options for a U.S. listing to increase the =
number of investors who can own PSH,=E2=80=9D because=C2=A0<em>obviously=C2=
=A0</em>marketing efforts=C2=A0<em>inside=C2=A0</em>the US will go over bet=
ter.=C2=A0But it didn=E2=80=99t work; it was too complicated to turn PSH in=
to a US company. So Ackman is starting a=C2=A0<em>new=C2=A0</em>US company =
to, I suspect, more or less clone PSH.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Presumably the expectation is that, by increas=
ing the number of investors who can own=C2=A0<em>some </em>flavor of Pershi=
ng Square, Ackman will be able to raise money at less of a discount. (Maybe=
 a premium?) Over time you raise most of your money in the US, in PSUS, whe=
re investors will pay more for the portfolio, and you do buybacks to retire=
 shares in Europe, in PSH, where they won=E2=80=99t.<a class=3D"footnote-in=
dex" href=3D"#footnote-7" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; disp=
lay: inline-block;">
<span>[7]</span>
</a>=C2=A0In 2014 Ackman raised his permanent capital in Europe, which work=
ed but was kind of an odd fit for his profile; in 2024 he will shift it mor=
e toward the US, which is a better fit. He can buy back PSH low and, probab=
ly, sell PSUS=C2=A0high.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other way to think about it is, look, you=
=E2=80=99ve got management fees and you=E2=80=99ve got performance fees. Wh=
en you are a young hotshot hedge fund manager just starting out, you want t=
hose performance fees. You don=E2=80=99t have that much money of your own (=
you are young), you plan to make a lot of money for your investors (you are=
 confident), and you want to take a lot of that performance for yourself. M=
anagement fees are nice, but not that important, because you can=E2=80=99t =
raise=C2=A0<em>that=C2=A0</em>much money when you=E2=80=99re just starting =
out.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But when you are a mature famous hedge fund ma=
nager, the performance fees are less important. You have billions of dollar=
s of your own money in the fund now, so if your performance is good you wil=
l make lots of money just on the appreciation of your own money. But the ma=
nagement fees are more attractive: You are now famous, so you can put out a=
 tweet and expect to raise=C2=A0<em>$10 billion=C2=A0</em>of new money, whi=
ch will pay you a $200 million fee forever.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=
=3D"#footnote-8" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inli=
ne-block;">
<span>[8]</span>
</a>=C2=A0That starts to look nice.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Not that nice, now. PSH <a href=3D"https://lin=
k.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34283789.285388/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdv=
di9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzIwMDI2NjAvMDAwMTE5MzEyNTI0MDI2MzAxL2Q2MjM3ODF=
kbjIuaHRtI2Q2MjM3ODFfMzA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB76b8b211" itemprop=3D"Sto=
ryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; =
text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-c=
olor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> return=
ed 26.7% to investors last year</a>, net of fees. The rough math is that, o=
n $12 billion of net assets, Pershing Square probably charged PSH investors=
 about $180 million of management fees and more than $400 million of perfor=
mance fees.=C2=A0Under the PSUS=C2=A0fee structure, investors would have do=
ne better =E2=80=94=C2=A0Pershing Square says their net return would have b=
een 30.6% =E2=80=94=C2=A0and Ackman would have done worse; he would have ch=
arged less than half as much in fees.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But in the long run, I mean, maybe you can=E2=
=80=99t be a hotshot hedge fund manager forever. But you can manage a perma=
nent capital vehicle forever; that=E2=80=99s the point. Raising enthusiasti=
c permanent capital when enthusiasm is high =E2=80=94=C2=A0and trading some=
 fees for permanence =E2=80=94 might be a good idea.</p>
