<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Block trades</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/34283789.285388/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL=
2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDEtMTYvbW9yZ2FuLXN0YW5sZXktbGVha2VkLXNvbWUtYmxvY2stdHJh=
ZGVzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAyMDgyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJ=
jZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDIwOCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607=
f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB92ad93f6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsco=
pe" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  talked last month</a> about some =
bad stuff that Morgan Stanley did in its block trading business. A big hold=
er of stock =E2=80=94=C2=A0say, a private equity firm with a big stake in a=
 company it had already taken public =E2=80=94=C2=A0would decide to sell th=
e stock all at once. It would call Morgan Stanley at like noon and say =E2=
=80=9Cwe want to sell all our stock in Company X, we=E2=80=99re going to as=
k you for a bid at 4:05 p.m. today, get ready, but=C2=A0<em>don=E2=80=99t t=
ell anyone</em>.=E2=80=9D And the holder would call a few other banks with =
the same message. And then Morgan Stanley was supposed to sit down and deci=
de what price to bid on the stock, and if it was the highest bidder at 4:05=
 p.m. it would win the block trade, buy the stock at its bid price, and the=
n turn around and sell the stock to hedge funds and other investors, as qui=
ckly as possible and preferably before the market opened the next day. But =
if it won the bid, it would be at risk: If it couldn=E2=80=99t sell the sto=
ck for more than it paid for it, it would lose money.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One thing that would make this process easier =
and less risky for Morgan Stanley would be if, between noon and 4 p.m., it =
were to call a bunch of hedge funds and say =E2=80=9Chey, we got a block of=
 Company X coming this evening, would you buy some, and if so for what pric=
e?=E2=80=9D If it pre-sold the block before putting in a bid, it could be c=
onfident that it would be able to resell the stock to investors and make mo=
ney. But the seller=C2=A0did not want Morgan Stanley to do that, because if=
 word leaked out about the block, people would know that a lot of supply wa=
s coming and that the stock would go down, so they would sell the stock fir=
st, which would lower the price that the seller could get. So the seller wo=
uld tell Morgan Stanley, in writing, emphatically, =E2=80=9Cdon=E2=80=99t t=
ell anyone about this block, don=E2=80=99t even drop any hints about it, do=
n=E2=80=99t have even generic conversations about the sector with investors=
, keep this really secret.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And Morgan Stanley would agree to those terms,=
 and then it would go out and tell a bunch of hedge funds about the block a=
nyway, and some of the hedge funds would short the stock and make a quick e=
asy profit when the block trade came, and the stock=C2=A0would go down and =
the seller=C2=A0would get a worse price=C2=A0and eventually Morgan Stanley =
got in trouble and paid several hundred million dollars in fines.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One lingering question might be: Should the=C2=
=A0<em>hedge funds=C2=A0</em>get in trouble? It sort of seems like Morgan S=
tanley had inside information, and it tipped that information to the hedge =
funds, and they traded on it. Is that bad?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It=E2=80=99s tricky. The <a href=3D"https://li=
nk.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34283789.285388/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21=
iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTQtMTItMTAvYXBwZWFscy1jb3VydC1ub3Qtc2=
8ta2Vlbi1vbi1pbnNpZGVyLXRyYWRpbmctY3JhY2tkb3duP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAyMDgyNF9NT05FW=
VNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI0=
MDIwOCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa976bd6c" i=
temprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: =
#ccc;">  traditional insider trading analysis</a> would say that it is ille=
gal to trade on information that someone has misappropriated, if you know (=
or ought to know) that it was misappropriated. If your brother-in-law is an=
 investment banker, and he tells you =E2=80=9Chey I=E2=80=99m working on a =
deal, you should buy call options=C2=A0on the target,=E2=80=9D you really o=
ught to know that he=E2=80=99s not supposed to do that.<a class=3D"footnote=
-index" href=3D"#footnote-9" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; d=
isplay: inline-block;">
<span>[9]</span>
</a>=C2=A0And=C2=A0many=C2=A0insider tips will look like that; you will hav=
e some reason to suspect that person telling you the information really sho=
uldn=E2=80=99t be.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">With the block trade leaks, the <a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34283789.285388/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu=
anVzdGljZS5nb3YvbWVkaWEvMTMzMzIwNi9kbA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1658df0a" i=
