<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One finance hypothetical that people like to p=
onder is: If 90% of the stock market was held by index funds, would that be=
 good or bad for efficiency? Would the prices of stocks better incorporate =
all information about those stocks, or worse? There are arguments both ways=
:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The negative view is that, if almost =
everyone indexes, there=E2=80=99s no one around to do the fundamental resea=
rch to make sure that prices are accurate. Hedge funds and other active man=
agers won=E2=80=99t have enough money to manage, they won=E2=80=99t be able=
 to invest in research and technology, and so there won=E2=80=99t be anyone=
 selling overvalued stocks and buying undervalued ones. It=E2=80=99ll just =
be index funds blindly buying at whatever the market price is, and that pri=
ce will be disconnected from fundamentals, and the stock market will no lon=
ger be good at allocating capital to its best uses. =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34283789.285388/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu=
Ymxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTYtMDgtMjQvYXJlLWluZGV4LWZ1bmR=
zLWNvbW11bmlzdD9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMjA4MjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJn=
V0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDAyMDgmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c=
3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa04e0531" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color:=
 #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; borde=
r-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc=
;">Passive Investing is Worse Than Marxism</a>,=E2=80=9D in the words of a =
somewhat famous Sanford C. Bernstein &amp; Co. equity research note.</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The positive view is that, the more mo=
ney that is indexed, the more=C2=A0<em>influence=C2=A0</em>each active mana=
ger will have on the stock. If most people index, then active management wi=
ll shrink, but the best active managers will keep their jobs, and their tra=
ding with each other is what will move stocks. Index funds will free-ride o=
n their efforts, but they will still have enough money to make those effort=
s worthwhile, and those efforts =E2=80=94=C2=A0not the free-riding =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0will determine the price.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#foot=
note-11" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none =
!important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block=
;">
<span>[11]</span>
</a>
</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is kind of an empirical question, though. H=
ere is =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34=
283789.285388/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubmJlci5vcmcvcGFwZXJzL3czMTk3NQ/607f07ceef4b85=
24a319a23cB58363c78" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decora=
tion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0000=
00; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Indexing and the I=
ncorporation of Exogenous Information Shocks to Stock Prices</a>,=E2=80=9D =
by=C2=A0Randall Morck and M. Deniz Yavuz, with some negative conclusions:</=
p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Savings increasingly flow to low-c=
ost index funds, which simply buy and hold the stocks in a major index, suc=
h as the S&amp;P 500. Increased indexing impedes incorporation of idiosyncr=
atic information into stock prices. We limit endogeneity bias by showing th=
at exogenous idiosyncratic currency shocks induce smaller idiosyncratic mov=
es in the stock prices of currency-sensitive firms in proximate time window=
s when in the index than when not in it. Increased indexing thus appears to=
 be undermining the efficient markets hypothesis that supports its viabilit=
y.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The basic idea is that there are some public c=
ompanies whose fundamental performance is particularly sensitive to exchang=
e rates: They do a lot of business in Europe (or wherever), and so their pr=
ofits fluctuate when the euro/dollar exchange rate goes up or down. An effi=
cient market would, arguably, reflect this: When the euro goes up, those co=
mpanies=E2=80=99 stocks would go up, or whatever. And they find that the ma=
rket is more efficient for companies outside the S&amp;P 500:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Our main tests reveal an economica=
lly and statistically significant 60% lower (-0.34 point estimate differenc=
e) in stocks=E2=80=99 idiosyncratic currency sensitivity when in versus not=
 in the S&amp;P 500, whereas the magnitude of idiosyncratic currency shocks=
 does not change significantly. The result is highly robust: It is evident =
in stocks added to the index, stocks dropped from the index, and both combi=
ned. It is robust across reasonable alternative ways of estimating idiosync=
ratic returns. Moreover, this difference in point estimate becomes more neg=
ative over time in lockstep with plausible proxies for the rising importanc=
e of indexing. These results are consistent with=C2=A0indexing impairing th=
e incorporation of firm-specific information into stock prices.</p></blockq=
uote>
